Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1944, General George Patton launched a bold plan to relieve the surrounded Allied forces in Bastogne, Belgium, during the Battle of the Bulge. 

The Germans aimed to capture Bastogne due to its strategic location at a critical road junction. Defended by the U.S. 101st Airborne Division, the town was under heavy siege, facing shortages of supplies amid harsh weather and constant German attacks. When asked to surrender, Brigadier General Anthony C. MacAuliffe famously responded with a single word: "Nuts."

Patton, known for his audacity, swiftly maneuvered his 3rd Army in a dramatic 90-degree turn, breaking through German lines to reach Bastogne. This timely intervention not only lifted the siege but also helped shift the momentum of the battle. Patton’s success played a key role in pushing the German forces back, eventually driving them eastward across the Rhine River, and marking a turning point in the Battle of the Bulge.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 2016, actress Carrie Fisher, best known for portraying Princess Leia in 𝑆𝑡𝑎𝑟 𝑊𝑎𝑟𝑠, dies at 60 years old. 

Her death came after she had a heart attack four days earlier on a flight from London. Fisher, the daughter of Hollywood stars Debbie Reynolds and Eddie Fisher, began her career in 1975 with 𝑆ℎ𝑎𝑚𝑝𝑜𝑜 and rose to fame as Leia in the 1977 𝑆𝑡𝑎𝑟 𝑊𝑎𝑟𝑠. Her portrayal of the strong, independent princess became iconic.

Fisher's other notable roles included parts in  𝑇ℎ𝑒 𝐵𝑙𝑢𝑒𝑠 𝐵𝑟𝑜𝑡ℎ𝑒𝑟𝑠 and 𝑊ℎ𝑒𝑛 𝐻𝑎𝑟𝑟𝑦 𝑀𝑒𝑡 𝑆𝑎𝑙𝑙𝑦. She also worked as a script doctor for films like 𝑇ℎ𝑒 𝑊𝑒𝑑𝑑𝑖𝑛𝑔 𝑆𝑖𝑛𝑔𝑒𝑟 and 𝑆𝑖𝑠𝑡𝑒𝑟 𝐴𝑐𝑡. In 2015, Fisher returned to her 𝑆𝑡𝑎𝑟 𝑊𝑎𝑟𝑠 role in 𝑇ℎ𝑒 𝐹𝑜𝑟𝑐𝑒 𝐴𝑤𝑎𝑘𝑒𝑛𝑠.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Mamie Scott is a dedicated resident of Enfield with 36 years in education and social work. She started as a teacher assistant and became a middle school dropout coordinator before transitioning to social work. As a social worker, she focused on helping at-risk students.

Mamie is also the Founder and CEO of the Community of Hope Center in Enfield, with the mission to positively impact the community’s mental, emotional, and physical well-being. The center provides food distribution, senior literacy classes, and social activities. It has also supported families with holiday meals and necessities.

Through her career and civic work, Mamie has received numerous awards for her contributions to the community. Her legacy of service continues to inspire and uplift the residents of Enfield, and we are glad to highlight her incredible work in helping eastern NC families. 

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
Good gracious, I came out of Christmas bliss to see arguments about American labor vs H1-B imported labor and MAGA split over this issue.

Good, that means everyone is engaged in saving this country.

Here is some tough reality for some of you:

There are some big MAGA voices with large social media platforms throwing down their opinions yet they have never run a company that relies on thousands of skilled/highly trained workers with a constant need for reliable labor yet they claim authority over the subject matter.

When you spend years trying to constantly hire/train/maintain a good reliable workforce, which is a 24/7 never ending cycle, your real world experience will produce an opinion based on reality and all of your followers on X don’t translate to this.

Having owned a construction company for decades (yes I’m that old), I know firsthand our workforce issues.

However, I fully believe we must make the hard and necessary changes here in the U.S. to educate, build, and facilitate a solid foundation of knowledgeable, highly skilled, talented, well paid, AMERICAN workers. 

Not having this is like having a crumbling foundation in our house and currently we are importing foreigners to hold up the foundation walls and plug the leaks. 

Too many of our young people, are killing their bodies and minds on alcohol and drugs, wasting years and money earning useless college degrees, chasing unrealistic dreams, spending all their time trying to be the next you tuber/content creator/social media influencer instead of pursuing a useful skill set/trade/education in order to become a part of our much needed American workforce. 

If you fall in this category, put down the selfie light, and go apply for a job and replace the H1-B visa holders and all the other skilled labor jobs that foreign workers are taking and American companies are desperately trying to hire.

It’s called building a career, you work your way up.

In order to go forward we must change our education system, create a culture that respects hard work and productivity, cut government waste/spending/regulations in order to produce a healthy robust economy that lowers inflation and pays higher wages to an American workforce, so that H1-B is no longer needed and can be done away with.

Decades of America LAST bad decisions in Washington wove a giant web of America LAST policies that created systems and structures that must be torn down and rebuilt to put America FIRST.

This requires everyone’s help to change it and we will all have to do what it takes to get it done.

It won’t be easy and it won’t be as quick as we like, but we can do it TOGETHER and the results will MAKE AMERICA GREAT AGAIN but EVEN BETTER THAN BEFORE!!!

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the stories of Hometown Heroes across our district—individuals whose actions inspire, uplift, and transform lives. Today, we honor an extraordinary collaboration that showcases the boundless strength of compassion and the transformative power of community. This week’s Hometown Heroes are the Northampton, Neshaminy, Middletown, and Bristol Senior Centers, along with the Bucks County Sheriff's Community Outreach Unit.
 
Together, this remarkable group of Seniors and law enforcement officers united to confront an urgent and often overlooked crisis: providing critical support to our homeless community during the coldest months of the year. For those without shelter, these unforgiving temperatures are not merely uncomfortable; they are life-threatening. A warm coat, sturdy shoes, or even a simple blanket can mean the difference between life and death.
 
Recognizing this dire need, they joined forces through the Sheriff's Help for the Holidays initiative, collecting and donating hundreds of winter necessities—coats, gloves, scarves, blankets, shoes, and more. Last Friday, CPL Todd Kessler and Deputy Dion Thomas joined Venus Johnson of the Reach Out Foundation, Rodney Wyatt of Salute 2 Service, members of the Bucks County Park Rangers, and Matt Allen, Director of Veterans Affairs, to deliver these vital resources directly to those in need. What they gave was not just warmth for the body but an uplifting message of hope, support, and holiday magic.
 
This effort was more than a seasonal gesture of kindness—it was a shining example of what makes Bucks County extraordinary. It highlighted the boundless generosity of our Seniors, the backbone of our community, and the exceptional commitment of our hero law enforcement officers, who demonstrated that when we work together, we can transform even the smallest gestures into a powerful beacon of hope.
 
To everyone who contributed to the success of Help for the Holidays, thank you. Your vision, leadership, and compassion addressed a critical need and left an indelible mark on our community. You remind us of the extraordinary difference we can make when we come together as one community.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1832, John Calhoun became the first U.S. vice president to resign due to political differences with President Andrew Jackson.

A strong advocate for states' rights and the agrarian South, Calhoun served as Secretary of War under James Monroe and briefly ran for president in 1824, before being forced out by partisan attacks. He became vice president under John Quincy Adams in 1824 and was re-elected in 1828 alongside Jackson. 

However, Calhoun soon became politically isolated from Jackson’s administration regarding the high tariff stance on imported goods preferred by the quickly industrializing North. Calhoun argued for nullification, allowing states to ignore federal laws they thought were unconstitutional. President Jackson declared nullification as treasonous and threatened military force when South Carolina declared tariffs null and void within the state. To remain loyal to his home state of South Carolina, Calhoun decided to represent the interests of the state in the Senate. He resigned from the vice presidency a few days before being elected to the Senate.

Name: Miller-Meeks, Mariannette
text:
President Carter was a dedicated public servant, honored veteran, and committed philanthropist. A peanut farmer turned Georgia governor, President Carter was a man devoted to his faith and teaching future generations as a Sunday School Teacher.  

And just as Ronald Reagan's nascent media career began in Iowa, so did Jimmy Carter’s presidential fortune. 

A dark horse candidate going into the 1976 Iowa Caucus, Carter used his interpersonal skills and background as a farmer to connect with Iowa voters. Placing 2nd, he captured the highest vote count of any other candidate, putting him on the map and the rest is history. 

I am praying for his family during this difficult time. I hope they find solace in knowing he is reunited with his wife Rosalynn in eternal rest.

Name: Norman, Ralph
text:
There something to said about a person's life when "President of the United States" could easily be a scant mention in his obituary.

President Carter was a graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy, and submariner in both the Atlantic and Pacific fleets. He was a business owner, local community leader, and Georgia state senator. Later, he served as the Governor of Georgia before being elected as President of the United States. He was the author of 32 books and the co-founder of the Carter Center, a non-profit public policy organization involved in a wide variety of efforts to help resolve international conflicts and promote democracy. He was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2002. In his spare time, President Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, worked to build or repair over 4,000 homes through Habitat for Humanity, according to that organization. And if ALL THAT weren't enough, he taught Sunday school and was a deacon in his church in Plains, Georgia.

What an incredible life of service, which was part of his Christian calling. Rest in peace, President Carter.

It is with a heavy heart that Robin and I join the nation in mourning the loss of former President Jimmy Carter. President Carter was a devoted father, loving husband, and decorated patriot.
 
Growing up on a peanut farm in Central Georgia, President Carter learned the value of an honest day’s work at an early age. His sense of duty led him to the Naval Academy in Annapolis, where he began a lifetime of public service. He was also a champion of philanthropic efforts in the decades following his presidency. President Carter was living proof that public service does not end with elected office.
 
On behalf of Georgians everywhere, Robin and I offer our deepest sympathies and prayers to the Carter family.

Name: Courtney, Joe
text:
America lost a great man today. President Jimmy Carter personified the highest form of public service, not just as Governor and President, but as an ensign in the U.S. Navy who rose to be one of Admiral Hyman G. Rickover’s select officers at the birth of the "Nuclear Navy".

In 2005, when the Navy sought to close Submarine Base New London, former President Carter stood by "Team Connecticut" in opposition to a plan which would have moved the Base’s fleet to his home state of Georgia. His decision to support "Team Connecticut" in the face of political pressure at home represents the integrity and honor he served with throughout his life. Today, eastern Connecticut maintains our proud role as Submarine Capital of the World thanks to former President Carter.

I join the American people in sending my deepest condolences and gratitude to the Carter family for his lifetime of service.

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
Today, our nation and our world has lost a leader who embodied dignity and decency, grace and goodness.  Paul and I join in mourning the loss of President Jimmy Carter and in giving thanks for his life, which was saintly in its devotion to public service and peace. 
 
At the heart of President Carter’s public service was his fervent commitment to honoring the spark of divinity within every person.  He always defended that spark: whether teaching Sunday school in his beloved Maranatha Baptist Church, brokering the landmark Camp David Accords to pave the way to peace or building homes with Habitat for Humanity.  As President, his work to restore integrity to the political arena during a difficult chapter in our history was a testament to his firm faith in the sanctity of the public good, which he always placed above his own.  After leaving the White House, he carried on his service — leading perhaps the most impactful post-presidency in history.  
 
President Carter’s love for his wife, First Lady Rosalynn Carter, is immortal.  Their beautiful bond and partnership in service were a wonder to behold.  May it be a comfort to their children, Jack, Chip, Jeff and Amy, and the entire Carter family that so many mourn their loss and are praying for them at this sad time.

text:
I was saddened to hear the news today of the passing of President Jimmy Carter at the age of 100. President Carter led an extraordinary life, rising from humble beginnings in Plains, Georgia, to serve as the 39th President of the United States.

After leaving office, President Carter's commitment to service grew even stronger. His humanitarian work with organizations like Habitat for Humanity, where he personally helped build homes for families in need, brought hope and shelter to countless Americans; and his efforts to help ensure integrity to democratic nations, left a positive impact on the world.

President Carter’s life was deeply rooted in his faith in Jesus Christ, which he shared openly by teaching Sunday school into his later years. He was a loyal husband, a dedicated family man, and a servant leader who inspired others through his actions. His faith, compassion, and tireless dedication to service have left an indelible mark on our nation’s history. May he rest in peace.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
Statement from Congressman Jonathan Jackson on the Passing of Former President Jimmy Carter

Today, we grieve the passing of Former President Jimmy Carter, a leader of unparalleled integrity and compassion who devoted his life to the pursuit of justice, equality, and peace. At 100 years old, he leaves behind a legacy that profoundly shaped our nation and the world.

President Carter’s dedication to civil rights was evident in his actions both before and during his presidency. As Governor of Georgia, he called for an end to segregation and publicly declared that the time for racial discrimination had passed. His bold leadership in the South during a time of immense tension sent a powerful message of inclusion and progress.

As president, Jimmy Carter demonstrated a deep commitment to addressing systemic inequalities affecting Black communities. His administration significantly increased federal appointments of African Americans to high-ranking positions, creating opportunities for representation in spaces of power. He also expanded funding for historically Black colleges and universities, understanding that education is a cornerstone of opportunity.

President Carter worked closely with my father, Reverend Jesse Jackson, to empower marginalized communities and advance the cause of economic justice. Their collaboration helped secure greater access to federal resources for minority-owned businesses, particularly through the Minority Business Development Agency, which Carter strengthened during his presidency. Together, they emphasized the importance of uplifting underserved communities through economic inclusion, employment opportunities, and community investment.

Beyond his presidency, President Carter continued to work alongside civil rights leaders like my father. He joined efforts to mediate racial and economic disparities, offering his wisdom and influence to bring people together in pursuit of equality. His efforts through the Carter Center tackled issues like voter suppression, housing insecurity, and global poverty, which disproportionately affect communities of color. His hands-on involvement with Habitat for Humanity built not just homes, but hope, for families striving for a better future.

President Carter’s moral leadership and tangible actions remind us that true progress requires not just words but deeds. He transformed the presidency into a platform for service and ensured that the fight for civil rights remained central to the American story.

On behalf of the constituents of Illinois’ 1st District, I extend my heartfelt condolences to the Carter family and to all those mourning this extraordinary man. May we honor his legacy by continuing his work to build a world where justice, dignity, and opportunity are within reach for all.

Rest in peace, President Carter. Your life’s work will forever inspire us.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1853, U.S. Minister to Mexico James Gadsden and Mexican President Antonio López de Santa Anna signed the Gadsden Purchase treaty in Mexico City, resolving a border dispute west of El Paso, Texas. 

The U.S. acquired approximately 30,000 square miles of land in present-day southern New Mexico and Arizona for $10 million, down from the initial $15 million. The land was considered strategically important for building a southern transcontinental railroad. U.S. Secretary of War Jefferson Davis had tasked Gadsden with negotiating the deal. Later, in 1861, prominent railroad figures—Collis P. Huntington, Leland Stanford, Mark Hopkins, and Charles Crocker—founded the Southern Pacific Railroad to develop the region.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text: The VA consistently matches or beats private-sector care in quality and patient satisfaction. It has built-in oversight that continually seeks improvement and accountability when things aren’t working well.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text: Despite the slick marketing attempt, the proposals would strip the VA of its core healthcare functions, reducing it to little more than a checkbook for private-sector (and less accountable) providers.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text:
The architects of this attack are following the lead of Concerned Veterans for America, a Koch-backed outfit that's long plotted VA privatization.

Feel-good buzzwords mask the ongoing takedown of the very system that millions of my fellow veterans and I rely on.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text:
Republican politicians’ stance on VA spending has become an exercise in fiscal fantasy.

They are carelessly pushing for unlimited private-sector siphoning of VA funds, consequences be damned.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text: But despite this reality, those with something to gain from this privatization agenda would rather lose that oversight, preferring to farm veterans out to lower-quality private providers instead of investing in the VA.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text: Rather than heed these warnings, my GOP colleagues are doubling down on the very policies that endanger the system. 4 of the bills don't just ignore the report's findings—they'd actively accelerate pushing more veterans & more money into pricier, private care with less oversight.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text:
When funding is shifted from the VA into private providers without replacement, VA facilities must cut staffing and programs that my fellow veterans rely on.

If we don’t act soon, the VA will be turned into another insurance company.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text: A March 2024 report authored by six independent healthcare experts laid bare an alarming reality: external private-sector spending is ballooning by 15-20% annually, an unsustainable rate that threatens to bleed the VA system dry. https://t.co/fHZMiBq4tV

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text:
It's like watching someone respond to warnings about a leaking boat by drilling more holes in the hull.

Name: Deluzio, Christopher R.
text:
The VA is being hollowed out in favor of profits.

This isn’t fiscal conservatism; it’s a deliberate choice to weaken and replace a valued public healthcare system with a more expensive (and worse) private alternative.

text:

3.5 million veterans get all their healthcare in-house at the VA—many of whom have service-related disabilities.

text: The leaders of the new Dept. are proposing cutting up to $119B from the VA and its healthcare program. If their vision comes to pass, it will essentially eliminate all types of healthcare, including primary, surgical, specialty, dental, mental health care—& a heck of a lot more.

Name: Timmons, William R.
text:
The American people made their wishes loud and clear on November 5, giving President Donald Trump a decisive victory and another term in office to turn our country around. Meanwhile, Republicans in the House retained the majority with a narrow margin. Our takeaway is clear: the mandate from the American people lies with President @realDonaldTrump, and his America First agenda is what the American people want.

Individual House Republicans do not get to use our slim majority as a political tool to hold President Trump’s agenda hostage. President Trump only has four years to get us back on track. That means on Day 1 we must all be prepared to work to enact Trump’s agenda, not to critique, slow walk it, or even block it from happening. That is what the Democrats will try to do at every turn. The defectors in Congress should not be Republicans who think they know better than the candidate who just won the popular vote and every single swing state, carrying many Rs to victory with him. 

Today President Trump offered his complete and total endorsement for Mike Johnson as Speaker of the House. I will proudly stand alongside President Trump and support @SpeakerJohnson. President Trump has a plan, and he needs us in Congress to work together to make that plan a reality. 

Lastly, I will say this. One cannot be America First and then defy the America First President. Members of Congress thinking they know better than President Trump will be the reason we do not deliver for the American people. We have one opportunity to save this country, but we have to work together to do that. I am looking forward to working with President Trump and the Republican Majority during the 119th Congress.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1999, the United States officially transferred control of the Panama Canal to Panama, marking the first time the waterway was under Panamanian ownership. 

The 50-mile canal, linking the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, had been in U.S. hands since its completion in 1914. Over one million ships had passed through the canal by then.

The idea of a canal across Panama dates back to the early 1500s, with various plans proposed but never realized. U.S. interest grew in the mid-1800s, spurred by the California Gold Rush and the need for a shortcut between the oceans.

President Theodore Roosevelt pushed for the project, and in 1903, Panama gained independence from Colombia with U.S. support. The U.S. and Panama signed the Hay-Bunau-Varilla Treaty, giving the U.S. control of the canal zone in exchange for a $10 million payment and annual rent.

In 1977, after decades of Panamanian protests, the Torrijos-Carter Treaties were signed, setting the stage for the 1999 handover. The treaties gave the U.S. the right to defend the canal's neutrality but handed control to Panama.

In 2024, we achieved real victories:

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
But the numbers only tell part of the story. 

We led efforts to combat toxic PFAS chemicals, expand mental and behavioral health and addiction resources, secured critical funding for groundbreaking cancer research, and introduced the bipartisan Let America Vote Act, a historic step to protect voting rights for all citizens. We passed H.R. 82, the Social Security Fairness Act, delivering long-overdue retirement justice for public servants, and advanced aviation safety with the passage of my Saracini Enhanced Aviation Act. We awarded the Congressional Gold Medal to the 6 million women who served as Rosie The Riveters during World War II, and passed historic legislation to award Billie Jean King the Congressional Gold Medal for her lifetime of advocacy. And in my role as Chairman of the National Intelligence Subcommittee, I fought to secure the release of 2 wrongfully detained Americans, including Tigran Gambaryan. 

What a year it’s been, but our work is far from over. As we look to 2025, I’m more determined than ever to keep moving forward, delivering real change and results for our entire PA-1 community.

Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
Challenge accepted.

First let me note that the “vote for Mike” camp is not trying to make the case that Mike Johnson is endowed with the qualities necessary to lead our conference. Even you have limited yourself here to procedural justifications for his speakership rather than telling us why he is a good or capable leader.

Even if Mike’s entire goal is to do everything Trump wants without debate or question (which I would argue is not healthy for the institution of Congress), he’s not going to be good at it. He already demonstrated this month that he won’t tell the President what is achievable and what is not achievable in the House, and he lacks the situational awareness himself to know what can pass and what cannot.

1. “What do we hope to gain?”
A competent Speaker who has the will and the ability to capitalize on this once in a decade opportunity. Johnson is not up for this task. Also, we want a Speaker who inspires the public and who can make our case in the media, so we can keep the majority for the second half of Trump’s term. Johnson nearly led us to the minority in what was a banner year for Trump. He is certain to lose us the majority in 2026.

2. “No one can get more votes.”
It’s somewhat ridiculous to assert that Mike Johnson is the only member of Congress electable to Speaker. He was only electable the first time because he hadn’t held any type of leadership position, nor had he ever fought for anything, so no one disliked him and everyone was tired of voting. He won by being the least objectionable candidate, and he no longer possesses that title.

3. “Risk crippling Trump’s win.”
This is argument is a scare tactic, meant to stampede the masses, plain and simple. There is no legal or parliamentary argument for nullifying the national election if a speaker is not in place on January 6th.

4. “They are allies of the democrats”
Actually it is Mike Johnson who routinely passes  major legislation (Ukraine, Omnibus, FISA spying) with only a minority of republicans, and relying on most democrats. He also owes his current speakership to the democrats. Here’s the roll call for the motion to table the motion to vacate last summer. Pelosi and Jeffries teamed up to save Johnson:
https://t.co/mNqgdbPClD

In closing, the emperor has no clothes and the entire conference knows it but few will say it. The general public knows it too. Please don’t shoot the messengers

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Did you know black-eyed peas were once dismissed as livestock feed but are now a cherished Southern New Year’s tradition? This humble dish carries a powerful story of survival, grit, and the enduring values of the South. Here’s why it matters. 🧵 https://t.co/XtPUgLcYg6

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: The story begins during the Civil War. As General Sherman’s Union forces marched through the South, they targeted crops to starve Confederate soldiers. Black-eyed peas, seen as animal feed, were left behind—becoming a vital source of nourishment for many Southerners. https://t.co/23OYQC9zyU

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Each part of the traditional New Year’s meal has meaning:
 - Black-eyed peas: Good fortune and prosperity (representing coins).
 - Greens (collards, kale, or cabbage): Wealth and abundance (resembling paper money).
 - Cornbread: Gold and overall sustenance.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: From this hardship, black-eyed peas became a symbol of resilience. Southerners took this overlooked food and turned it into a powerful tradition—a reminder that even in the toughest times, we can persevere and rebuild.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Black-eyed peas carry layers of history—stories of resilience, survival, and the tough decisions that shaped our nation. They remind us that grit and hope can carry us through even the hardest times.

Name: Bera, Ami
text:
As we look ahead to 2025, I want to highlight some of Team Bera's efforts to deliver for #SacramentoCounty during the 118th Congress.

Our team resolved over 6,600 constituent cases and returned more than $5,000,000 to Sacramento County taxpayers. This includes assisting #CA06 residents with stalled passports and tax returns, helping seniors access Social Security and Medicare benefits, and ensuring veterans receive the benefits they have earned.

We also secured over $295,000,000 in federal funding and grants for Sacramento County. From upgrading our infrastructure to growing our economy, I’m excited about the investments we are making in the Sacramento region's future.

If you or someone you know needs assistance from our office, please visit my website at https://t.co/zaW7gvWsXF to learn more about how we can help.

Wishing you and your loved ones a happy, healthy, and prosperous new year!
